WEBVTT

p01
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.397
This is the Command Center, the first screen your network hands you.

p02
00:00:03.761 --> 00:00:05.458
It looks like a wall of numbers. It isn't.

p03
00:00:05.722 --> 00:00:08.946
It's a triage board, stacked top to bottom.

p04
00:00:09.414 --> 00:00:12.726
Read the stack in order, and the thing that needs you rises to the top.

p05
00:00:13.276 --> 00:00:15.042
First panel, the mobile app.

p06
00:00:15.769 --> 00:00:20.308
That Live tag means the figures move on their own, refreshing as members open the app.

p07
00:00:20.805 --> 00:00:24.570
You're reading its pulse right now, not a report someone ran this morning.

p08
00:00:25.195 --> 00:00:29.627
For a network pushing an app, this is the first read on whether members actually use it.

p09
00:00:30.070 --> 00:00:31.296
Four cards across.

p10
00:00:32.218 --> 00:00:35.034
Installs, weekly actives, redemptions, opt-in rate.

p11
00:00:35.242 --> 00:00:35.989
Linger on redemptions: it splits Q-R scans from kiosk taps,

p12
00:00:36.921 --> 00:00:38.276
so you see whether members cash in at the phone or at the machine.

p13
00:00:38.492 --> 00:00:48.000
That split tells you which channel is carrying the program.

p14
00:00:48.384 --> 00:00:49.772
Scroll to the map panel.

p15
00:00:50.665 --> 00:00:52.405
The heading counts the whole network: a hundred forty-four sites across seven states.

p16
00:00:52.885 --> 00:00:55.526
That color key beside it, healthy, warning, critical, is the same key the pins use.

p17
00:00:56.066 --> 00:01:06.560
Once you know the key, the map tells you where to look without reading a single label.

p18
00:01:06.958 --> 00:01:08.804
Down the left, four vitals.

p19
00:01:09.115 --> 00:01:10.959
Money in today, who's active, cars through the tunnels,

p20
00:01:11.344 --> 00:01:14.569
and the share of card charges that bounced.

p21
00:01:14.930 --> 00:01:19.057
That last one, the decline rate, is what a support tech watches closest,

p22
00:01:19.368 --> 00:01:23.658
because a climbing decline rate usually means a billing problem, not a slow day.

p23
00:01:24.096 --> 00:01:25.408
Now the map itself.

p24
00:01:26.517 --> 00:01:28.746
Every pin is a wash, colored by health, so a red dot is a site in trouble at a glance.

p25
00:01:29.188 --> 00:01:32.108
Hover one and it shows that site's revenue, members, and tickets, with a link to open it.

p26
00:01:32.683 --> 00:01:41.951
Not today, though. We're reading the network, not diving into a single site.

p27
00:01:42.410 --> 00:01:44.531
Click Active States, then Full USA.

p28
00:01:44.531 --> 00:01:47.889
The map reframes, and that's all it does.

p29
00:01:47.889 --> 00:01:49.559
This toggle is view-only.

p30
00:01:49.559 --> 00:01:53.801
It changes the shot, never the data, and never the panels below.

p31
00:01:53.801 --> 00:01:55.861
One click puts it back.

p32
00:01:56.415 --> 00:01:57.786
Here's the heart of the page.

p33
00:01:58.293 --> 00:01:59.802
Priority Intelligence, eleven items, four urgent.

p34
00:02:00.005 --> 00:02:02.036
It's your triage feed, sorted by severity,

p35
00:02:02.671 --> 00:02:05.232
and every row is a door onto the module where you'd actually fix it.

p36
00:02:05.455 --> 00:02:12.604
For a support tech, this is the panel you scan first.

p37
00:02:13.055 --> 00:02:14.566
Top of the feed, Critical.

p38
00:02:15.017 --> 00:02:20.204
Two rows, and this is where a downed P-O-S shows up first, before the phone even rings.

p39
00:02:20.649 --> 00:02:23.621
Open jumps you to reconciliation to work the outage.

p40
00:02:24.058 --> 00:02:27.742
Review drops you into Support for the tickets about to breach their S-L-A.

p41
00:02:28.181 --> 00:02:30.037
Next tier, High Priority.

p42
00:02:30.419 --> 00:02:36.768
A kiosk printer down, a site's conversion slipping.

p43
00:02:37.208 --> 00:02:38.523
Not on fire yet, but they will be if they sit.

p44
00:02:38.820 --> 00:02:42.747
Watch the verbs shift: Assign hands the work off, Analyze opens the numbers behind it.

p45
00:02:43.229 --> 00:02:44.139
Now the money.

p46
00:02:44.740 --> 00:02:45.719
Revenue Plays, five suggestions worth thirty-two hundred dollars today,

p47
00:02:46.054 --> 00:02:49.019
each tagged with what it's worth.

p48
00:02:49.418 --> 00:02:50.877
Read them as prompts, not orders.

p49
00:02:51.413 --> 00:02:53.424
Launch, Target, Recover, those fire real outreach to real customers,

p50
00:02:54.153 --> 00:03:02.312
so on a live tenant you look, you don't press.

p51
00:03:02.744 --> 00:03:03.491
Last group, Automations.

p52
00:03:03.772 --> 00:03:04.592
Two jobs already running with no one steering,

p53
00:03:05.210 --> 00:03:13.090
a win-back text sequence and the payment retry engine, quietly clawing back failed charges.

p54
00:03:13.796 --> 00:03:16.413
Inspect and View check on them without touching a thing,

p55
00:03:16.818 --> 00:03:19.352
which is just what you want with something already working.

p56
00:03:19.778 --> 00:03:21.935
One habit ties this panel together.

p57
00:03:22.302 --> 00:03:24.381
Read the arrow before you click.

p58
00:03:24.812 --> 00:03:28.557
Open, Review, View, those take you somewhere to look.

p59
00:03:28.958 --> 00:03:31.585
Launch, Target, Recover, Assign, those start something.

p60
00:03:31.874 --> 00:03:33.190
Read arrows are safe.

p61
00:03:33.636 --> 00:03:39.003
Action arrows you leave alone here, on a shared live tenant.

p62
00:03:39.476 --> 00:03:40.201
To the right, Action Ownership.

p63
00:03:40.423 --> 00:03:41.483
Same items, now answered by who owns them and when they're due.

p64
00:03:41.781 --> 00:03:45.321
Regional Ops on the outage within the half hour, Support on the aging tickets,

p65
00:03:45.746 --> 00:03:55.227
Marketing and Revenue on the plays.

p66
00:03:55.429 --> 00:03:56.640
It answers the question a manager always asks: whose job is this.

p67
00:03:57.084 --> 00:03:59.000
At the bottom, Ask MAIA.

p68
00:03:59.506 --> 00:04:03.885
Five plain-language shortcuts, each jumping straight to the module that answers it.

p69
00:04:04.571 --> 00:04:10.086
Worth flagging: the header button reads Ask Shyne, this panel reads Ask MAIA.

p70
00:04:10.447 --> 00:04:15.677
Two names, so we don't tell a client they're one feature yet, and we send neither one today.

p71
00:04:16.129 --> 00:04:18.630
Scroll back up, and you've got the whole board.

p72
00:04:19.166 --> 00:04:25.120
App engagement, the network map, the priority feed, who owns what, and a shortcut to ask.

p73
00:04:25.649 --> 00:04:27.386
Five panels, one screen.

p74
00:04:27.783 --> 00:04:31.975
Read it top to bottom, and never click an arrow until you know which kind it is.

p75
00:04:32.427 --> 00:04:36.237
Do that, and the Command Center works for you, not against you.

